RODEO IS HOME SAFELY!! The sweet and lovely couple from the Bear Swamp Orchard & Cidery went out hiking, called to her, and she came right to them! Miracle of miracles! 
I can't even begin to imagine repaying the kindness shown to us by this incredible community, near and far. A special shining thank you to pretty much the entire population of Ashfield, who - even for total strangers, and not even residents in the town - wholeheartedly showed up with so much fierce support I was completely blown away. What a gift to be held by such an incredible force! I do hope this message reaches everyone who spread the word for us, shared amazingly thoroughly on social media (you guys get shit done!), printed flyers, called their friends, fervently searched the deep woods, and had a little worry in their hearts for our tiny family. I will be forever in your debt! We couldn't have done it without you. 
Although she is sleepy and a little sore from her adventure, she has indulged in a proper meal, enjoyed her favorite toy, and is now getting some much-deserved rest in her cozy bed. We are also off to eat a proper meal and gaze lovingly at our sweet lady. 
Thank you all so so much, from the bottom of our desperately exhausted hearts. <3 (also! A glowing recommendation to Jamie and Dexter from Packleader Pettrackers. They are an incredible team and I hope that you never need their services, but if you do, don't hesitate!) (alsooooo.... a last request - if you see a sign around, please feel free to take it down with a flourish! And pat yourself on the back for a job well done! <3) 
Please share this as widely as you all did before! Y'all are incredible! ğŸ’–ğŸ™ŒğŸ’–

Researchers in Alberta are trying to determine whether GPS technology can help people with early stage dementia stay safe and live independently longer.

The Locator Device Project is a six-month trial being conducted out of the University of Alberta.

Ah, just when I was about ready to write my review of the @taggpettracker, the whole thing gets switched over to @whistlelabs and now I have to do all my tests over again! Feels about it so far though? It's just not fast enough to track Si in the event she's whisked away by some nefarious dog napper. If I press the track button, it's often several minutes before I get a location. Imagine a person driving off with your service dog: they'd be long gone! With the new app out today I wasn't able to get a location on Si at all! As part of my review, I've been doing research and looking at other pet tracker options. This was the cheapest one, but probably not gonna keep up with the monthly fee since it's just not accurate or 'real time' enough, unless improvements are made in the very near future.

By @jo.michaela "1 hour later, we finally found this guy thanks to #Tagg Pet Tracker.

Last night, @byjad's apartment building was struck by lightening and the firefighters had to come and kick in all the doors to make sure no apartments caught on fire. In doing this, Joey (who must've already been panicking), ran out of the door and into the neighborhood. Joey's Pet Tracker device on his collar went off immediately, notifying Josh that he was out if his home zone. Though the GPS tracking only updates every few minutes to conserve battery, it was showing his updated range of location consecutively. It turns out Joey spent a long time in thick, thorny, briar patch-like bushes that we would have NEVER found him in were it not for this #pettracker. Not in a million years.

We were able to get two police offers help us navigate through the thick meadow to come around and into the woods behind Joey, who was scared and not responding to our voices. After a long while, we were finally able to retrieve this sweetest dog.

After this experience, I want to explain something. I was so skeptical about this device. It's about $100 to purchase and I thought to myself "That's silly. Joey's never going to get out of the apartment". This morning I take back everything I said in doubt if this device. If it weren't for it, Joey would not be safe and warm in Josh's apartment today chewing on a bone and playing with his toys. 
If you have a pet, please consider looking into trackin devices. They could mean the difference between finding or losing a member of your family."

This guy likes to escape, and run as fast as possible. Unfortunately, we live in a neighborhood where he could easily hide. Picked up a Tagg  Pet Tracker on Sunday for him. Now I can see exactly where he is at all times and monitor his activity in realtime. I've been looking for a GPS device for him for a while but most require their own hand held device to monitor, but this one runs off a free app on Android and iPhone. The unit is fairly small and goes nearly unnoticed on his collar. Docking station stays wherever you want to keep his " Tagg Zone" Mine is inside the house. If he leaves the zone I'm notified by the app as well as text and/or email, depending on how you set it up. Different modes can be set if you plan to leave the zone so you aren't constantly alerted. If he does get out though you can track his path, and turn by turn directions are given on the map to lead you right to them. The tracker also alerts you if the device has been removed (I've yet to try this). So far I'm very impressed with the product. I'll report back with more details once we use it a bit more.

RODEO IS HOME SAFELY!! The sweet and lovely couple from the Bear Swamp Orchard & Cidery went out hiking, called to her, and she came right to them! Miracle of miracles! 
I can't even begin to imagine repaying the kindness shown to us by this incredible community, near and far. A special shining thank you to pretty much the entire population of Ashfield, who - even for total strangers, and not even residents in the town - wholeheartedly showed up with so much fierce support I was completely blown away. What a gift to be held by such an incredible force! I do hope this message reaches everyone who spread the word for us, shared amazingly thoroughly on social media (you guys get shit done!), printed flyers, called their friends, fervently searched the deep woods, and had a little worry in their hearts for our tiny family. I will be forever in your debt! We couldn't have done it without you. 
Although she is sleepy and a little sore from her adventure, she has indulged in a proper meal, enjoyed her favorite toy, and is now getting some much-deserved rest in her cozy bed. We are also off to eat a proper meal and gaze lovingly at our sweet lady. 
Thank you all so so much, from the bottom of our desperately exhausted hearts. <3 (also! A glowing recommendation to Jamie and Dexter from Packleader Pettrackers. They are an incredible team and I hope that you never need their services, but if you do, don't hesitate!) (alsooooo.... a last request - if you see a sign around, please feel free to take it down with a flourish! And pat yourself on the back for a job well done! <3)

Researchers in Alberta are trying to determine whether GPS technology can help people with early stage dementia stay safe and live independently longer.

The Locator Device Project is a six-month trial being conducted out of the University of Alberta.
With partial funding from the provincial government, researchers are testing out GPS technology to locate wandering or lost people who have cognitive impairments.

Tim Warman joined the study after his wife Allison, who suffers from early stage dementia, had a scare.

Ah, just when I was about ready to write my review of the @taggpettracker, the whole thing gets switched over to @whistlelabs and now I have to do all my tests over again! Feels about it so far though? It's just not fast enough to track Si in the event she's whisked away by some nefarious dog napper. If I press the track button, it's often several minutes before I get a location. Imagine a person driving off with your service dog: they'd be long gone! With the new app out today I wasn't able to get a location on Si at all! As part of my review, I've been doing research and looking at other pet tracker options. This was the cheapest one, but probably not gonna keep up with the monthly fee since it's just not accurate or 'real time' enough, unless improvements are made in the very near future.

By @jo.michaela "1 hour later, we finally found this guy thanks to #Tagg Pet Tracker.

Last night, @byjad's apartment building was struck by lightening and the firefighters had to come and kick in all the doors to make sure no apartments caught on fire. In doing this, Joey (who must've already been panicking), ran out of the door and into the neighborhood. Joey's Pet Tracker device on his collar went off immediately, notifying Josh that he was out if his home zone. Though the GPS tracking only updates every few minutes to conserve battery, it was showing his updated range of location consecutively. It turns out Joey spent a long time in thick, thorny, briar patch-like bushes that we would have NEVER found him in were it not for this #pettracker. Not in a million years.

We were able to get two police offers help us navigate through the thick meadow to come around and into the woods behind Joey, who was scared and not responding to our voices. After a long while, we were finally able to retrieve this sweetest dog.

After this experience, I want to explain something. I was so skeptical about this device. It's about $100 to purchase and I thought to myself "That's silly. Joey's never going to get out of the apartment". This morning I take back everything I said in doubt if this device. If it weren't for it, Joey would not be safe and warm in Josh's apartment today chewing on a bone and playing with his toys. 
If you have a pet, please consider looking into trackin devices. They could mean the difference between finding or losing a member of your family."

This guy likes to escape, and run as fast as possible. Unfortunately, we live in a neighborhood where he could easily hide. Picked up a Tagg  Pet Tracker on Sunday for him. Now I can see exactly where he is at all times and monitor his activity in realtime. I've been looking for a GPS device for him for a while but most require their own hand held device to monitor, but this one runs off a free app on Android and iPhone. The unit is fairly small and goes nearly unnoticed on his collar. Docking station stays wherever you want to keep his " Tagg Zone" Mine is inside the house. If he leaves the zone I'm notified by the app as well as text and/or email, depending on how you set it up. Different modes can be set if you plan to leave the zone so you aren't constantly alerted. If he does get out though you can track his path, and turn by turn directions are given on the map to lead you right to them. The tracker also alerts you if the device has been removed (I've yet to try this). So far I'm very impressed with the product. I'll report back with more details once we use it a bit more.
